defaultThose prohibitions, set out in the Competition Act 1998 (CA98)
default3 
defaultand the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU)
default4 
defaultapply to the conduct of all '
defaultundertakings
default'. 
defaultIn making this assessment, it is the nature of the particular activity being conducted that is key, not the legal form, or public or private sector status, of the body that carries it out. Thus, a body – including a public body – may be an undertaking (and therefore subject to competition law) in respect of some of its activities, but not others.
default 
default 
defaultIt is also important to note that this 'functional' approach means that a public body may act as an undertaking – and therefore be subject to competition law – in respect of some of its activities, but not in respect of others
